hi everyone nothiny dice Tano here the
internet's busiest music nerdy and it's
time for a review of this new Yaya Yaz
record cool it down this is a brand new
LP from Landmark New York Indy and
garage Rock Revival outfit Yeah Yeahs
Karen O Brian Chase and Nick zinner are
back releasing with this LP just short
of the 20th year anniversary of their
breakout debut it has also almost been
10 years since the release of the band's
last record mosquito which needless to
say was not received well by most fans
and critics alike and was frankly kind
of a sour note to leave things on for
such a long time I was hoping with so
much time having passed the band would
sound revitalized in some way on this
new project but I can't say that was my
listening experience now you could argue
this thing is the band's most mature
record yet I think if you said that
you'd be correct but in the process of
gaining that it seems like a lot of the
group's original thrill has been lost in
the process be because this is a pretty
non-descript project to drop from a band
that at one time was so raw was so bold
and was so definitive the opening track
spinning off the edge of the world I was
split on it when I first heard it and I
am still split on it now the pacing
generally on this track is pretty
tedious the CRP wall of droning buzzing
washed out synthesizers isn't exactly
the most inspired sound palette not for
four whole minutes anyway and obviously
Karen O's vocals continue to be a
selling point for the band of the
inclusion of perfume Genius is a nice
touch too but now it feels like Carano
is like the only selling point of the
band you could easily pop any number of
CopyCat Indie pop or Rock lead singers
into this song and you would pretty much
strip away any sense that this was a
Yeah Yeahs track entirely then from here
we have the song Love bomb and generally
I have nothing against a slow burner but
kicking your record off with two of them
I think is a questionable move
especially when once again we have a
similarly blank and synthy mix on our
hands vocally I would say Karen gives a
pretty haunting performance but she
doesn't really offer all that much on
the lyrical end of things wolf however
is the first real attempt at a Bop on
the album however uh its full potential
is soiled by these horrendously
overbearing synth strings on the chorus
it kind of sounds like if you took an
MGMT single from the first record and
remixed it for the golf club and no I
don't mean that in a good way with The
Punchy dance beat and fat distorted bass
line on fleas I feel like the band
inadvertently wrote a Death from Above
1979 track here but with some groovy
spacious Post Punk bits laced in between
also big UPS on the ESG nod in the
lyrics burning I would say is the first
moment on the lp I'm actually truly
enamored with it's certainly grown on me
since I first heard it as a single and
it's pretty much like if the band was
trying to write a grand anthemic rock
song Meant For A 007 soundtrack or intro
and I would actually love to see this
track reach that potential or I don't
know maybe some kind of awesome Netflix
sync things from here are on the record
cool down though there's the Mind
numbing beats and totally uninspired
chord progression of blacktop which does
slowly thicken up into this pretty
beautiful drone of bass synths and
guitar layers but once more this track
doesn't really leave a super strong
impression I enjoy it more as a Vibe
than I do a song and with this record
being so short it just feels like so
much effort to be sunk into something
that comes off so temporary then
curiously from here the band breaks into
this swaggerific bit of sophistic pop on
different today that somehow sounds like
something off destroyers could put not
sure how we got here but what I do know
is that this comes off pretty derivative
and I wouldn't say it's a sound Yaya's
cell particularly well then the closing
track Mars is a heartening spoken word
piece where Karen makes reference to her
son in a very touching way I won't spoil
the contents of the track but I will say
it feels like a very unsatisfying
send-off for a record that wasn't really
doing all that much for the half hour
that it lasted but yeah pretty much one
song that I loved here here while
everything else while not terrible was
just kind of all right just okay nothing
that I would be excited to return to
anytime soon which is putting me truly
on the fence with this LP as much as I
did want to be excited for it and kind
of feeling a light to decent five on
this one transition have you given this
